(41, 5, 12, 18, 1, 10, 12, NULL, 'Authority Over Evil Spirits', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority over evil. In Mark 5:12, the devils seek permission to enter the swine, while in Job 1:12, God grants Satan power over Job''s possessions, illustrating the control God has over spiritual forces.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 12, 42, 22, 31, 32, NULL, 'Connection of Spiritual Struggle', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual conflict, as both passages depict entities seeking to exert influence over individuals. In Mark, the devils desire to enter the swine, while in Luke, Satan desires to sift Simon, illustrating the ongoing battle between good and evil.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 12, 47, 2, 11, 11, 'devils besought him', 'Connection of Demonic Influence', 'This connection highlights the theme of demonic influence present in both passages. In Mark, the devils seek to enter the swine, while in 2 Corinthians, the warning against Satan''s devices suggests awareness of such influences.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 12, 60, 5, 8, 8, 'devil', 'Connection of Adversarial Forces', 'This connection highlights the presence of evil forces in both passages. In Mark, the devils seek to inhabit the swine, while in 1 Peter, the devil is depicted as a predator seeking to devour.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 12, 18, 2, 5, 5, NULL, 'Connection of Demonic Influence', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of demonic influence on human suffering. In Mark, the devils seek to enter the swine, while in Job, the adversary challenges God''s protection over Job''s flesh.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 13, 11, 22, 22, 22, 'unclean spirits', 'Spirits and Deception Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of unclean spirits influencing actions. In Mark, the unclean spirits enter the swine, while in 1 Kings, a lying spirit influences prophets.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 13, 18, 2, 6, 6, 'unclean spirits went out', 'Authority Over Evil Spirits', 'This connection highlights the authority of God over unclean spirits in both passages. In Mark, Jesus commands the unclean spirits to leave, while in Job, God permits Satan to afflict Job, demonstrating divine control over spiritual forces.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 13, 40, 8, 32, 32, 'ran violently down a steep place into the sea', 'Connection of Swine and Sea', 'Both passages emphasize the unclean spirits entering the herd of swine, which then ran violently down a steep place into the sea. This parallel action in both accounts illustrates the dramatic outcome of the exorcism.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 13, 43, 8, 44, 44, 'unclean spirits', 'Connection of Evil Spirits', 'This connection highlights the presence of evil, as seen in the unclean spirits entering the swine in Mark and the reference to the devil in John. Both passages emphasize the destructive nature of evil, with the swine''s demise paralleling the devil''s role as a murderer.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 13, 60, 3, 22, 22, 'unclean spirits went out', 'Authority Over Spirits and Powers', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' authority over unclean spirits in Mark 5:13 and His exalted position over angels and powers in 1 Peter 3:22. Both passages emphasize the subjugation of spiritual entities to Christ''s command.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 13, 18, 1, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection of Authority Over Spirits', 'This connection highlights the authority of Jesus and God over unclean spirits. In both passages, there is a transfer of power, with Jesus allowing spirits to enter swine and God permitting Satan to act within limits.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 5, 13, 66, 9, 11, 11, 'unclean spirits went out', 'Connection of Unclean Spirits and Destruction', 'This connection highlights the theme of unclean spirits leading to destruction. In Mark, the unclean spirits enter the swine, causing their demise, while in Revelation, the king of the bottomless pit represents destruction and chaos.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
